<br>
By comparison, the pickup raids that Torm, Vet, and I run are nice and orderly.  Most of the people who join us are experienced raiders, and we have a core group of people who come along on a lot of our raids.  We have more time to answer questions, and a lot of the other people on the raid can tell newbies what they should be doing because they've been on our raids before.  If we're raiding a plane or a zone like The Hole, there will be a long series of fights that allow people to learn to work together as a group.  In fact, one of the most amazing things about pickup raids is watching a bunch of total strangers transform into a cohesive fighting machine over the course of a few hours.<br>
<br>
Dragon raids don't have any of those luxuries.  Sometimes things click, sometimes they don't.  When things go bad, the raid leader usually gets blamed by some of the participants.  Sometimes the raid leader deserves the blame.<br>
<br>
From what I've read in this thread, I don't see that Moltie did anything wrong other than maybe not communicating as well as she could have, and maybe losing her temper and scapegoating some people.  Given the difficulty of running a dragon raid, and the stress that goes with it, those are pretty minor sins.  It sounds to me like Moltie did a pretty good overall job of running this raid. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/umoltaenyadmagmus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Moltaenya D Magmus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 62<br> <font color=#E9D756>(9/29/01 11:19:01 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> :)</span><hr size=1> Tee hee - someone actually called me Moltie.<br>
