<br>
     Yes, Chamcham is level 60.  So what if she is.  Being level 60, or just having a level 60 character, does not mean I'm God, or a god, or any immortal figure.  I can still lose exp.  If I was caught in a death loop or couldn't get res'd after dying more than once, yes I would be pissed off.  Experience DOES matter to me when I'm really into playing the game.  If I am playing a &quot;twink&quot; and I go out to kill stuff and die, then go back to kill something and die again, and can't get back on my feet and end up with less exp than I started then yes I would be pretty moody.  Not on a raid, though.  On a raid you can expect you lose at least some exp.<br>
     On my first dragon Naggy raid when I was in Phoenix Crusaders a long time ago we were told to bind at the corner before Naggy and what ended up happening was we had a wipe out and the Fire Giants began respawning on us (it was the same day they made Naggy and Vox banish people over level 52 and MS had just been ported out), and I was stuck in a death loop, lost half of my level and the level itself.  This was also before they made the change to how long your corpse hangs around if it has nothing on it, so those 6 other itemless bodies were all gone.  Yes, I was pretty angry, but then again that was a long time ago.  I was a bit paranoid of going on another dragon raid since.<br>
     I lose bundles of experience on each raid I go on simply because there's no way around the huge agro all my spells create on my targets, and usually I don't have enough spots of something like Memory Blu so I fall back on the others while I try doing my job with monsters laying the smack down.  All in all when it's a raid you're going on, being it an experienced raid or a huge anonymous pick up raid, you can expect at least one person to die most of the time.<br>
<br>
     And Dreadwolff, if you can remember...  People above level 52 can't go on Naggy/Vox raids.  They're banished outside the zone upon agro.  My ranger was on that raid and I'm pretty serious about improving him and keeping him in fit condition.  If I see something that can upgrade that character even in the least way then I'll try getting it.  My ranger was the one that died in that raid, it was impossible for Chamcham to die there.  I lost a half bubble of experience in level 52 permanently, and so did Moltaenya, what ever level she is (I can never tell these days).  I like my ranger a lot, no matter how many stupid crude jokes people crack about them, and if anything real serious happened to it I would probably freak out like Tuasai did.<br>
     Losing some experience I could easily get back in a day or less isn't that serious to me.  If I had some kind of plan or something set in my head that was like &quot;Okay, I'm going to make so much exp today, tomorrow, and hit the next level on blah-day.&quot;, then died a whole bunch, yes I would be mad.  Upset rather.  I said that clerics could get groups easily because... it's true.  You don't see many groups in the higher levels who go around the big exp areas without one.<br>
<br>
     Tuasai, I was not a raid leader.  I was a plain raider just like you on that day.  You may think I was because I was your group leader, but the three leaders were kind of mentioned in that chat room (Moltaenya, Archaeon, Khaliz) giving out instructions for the raid.  I didn't necessarily &quot;disappear&quot;.  When I died fighting Vox my computer stopped loading at the &quot;LOADING, PLEASE WAIT...&quot;, so I had to restart.  I came back up in Thurgadin next to Dararu and Truespirit, equipped my ranger with my secondary suit (my full suit of blackened iron and my spare weapons) and some money, and I set off out of Thurgadin after saying some things to Dararu and Truespirit so I could try getting back to Permafrost again in case there was any way possible Zelgadis could help with Corpse Recovery.  If you wanted to say or ask anything of me then you should have then.  I was not given orders to look after everyone in the group that was set up with us.  All I know is my job there was simply to seek the four people out and invite them so we could get a move on and beat the hell out of things.<br>
     When I was crossing the bridge to Great Divide in Thurgadin I got a tell asking me to log on Chamcham and give Ironlute (Moltaenya) the money from earlier on from Gorndax (Archaeon).  I decided I would stay on Chamcham and get to Permafrost and help out that way with Clarity 2, Haste, Bedlam, etc since I figured I was not an important figure in that raid.  I'm sure that IF I were one of the raid leaders in the raid then I would have some sort of purpose in the raid chat or something with handing out instructions. *shrug*  The raid was fruitless to someone like me since I already have a RBB.  I actually just considered myself friendly support for Moltaenya and not a greedy suck up.  I was around when Moltaenya said &quot;Hey Gorn, Chamcham, let's try a Vox raid!&quot;, but I was not in any way a raid leader.<br>
<br>
If you really wanted to ask me what was up, you could have asked people on the raid, or people in my guild, where I moved to.  I don't give up on people, and I really feel bad if I feel I have to leave and/or ignore someone who's in dire need of help.<br>
